topics.example:
try {
    int a = 10 / 0;   // risky code
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero");
}

Execution Step-by-Step:
1. JVM enters try block -> Executes 10 / 0
2. Exception occurs -> ArithmeticException
3. JVM stops normal flow
4. Searches matching catch block
5. Executes catch -> Program continues

try {
    int arr[] = new int[2];
    arr[5] = 10;
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Arithmetic Error");
} catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
    System.out.println("Array Index Error");
}

Working:
JVM checks catch blocks top to bottom. Executes the FIRST matching one.

try {
    int a = 10 / 2;
} catch (Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Always runs");
}

THROW:
static void checkAge(int age) {
    if (age < 18) throw new ArithmeticException("Not eligible");
}

THROWS:
static void readFile() throws IOException {
    FileReader file = new FileReader("test.txt");
}

class InvalidAmountException extends Exception {
    public InvalidAmountException(String msg) { super(msg); }
}

class Bank {
    void withdraw(int amount) throws InvalidAmountException {
        if (amount > 1000) throw new InvalidAmountException("Limit exceeded");
    }
}
// Working: Condition fails -> throws custom exception -> JVM catches and prints message.

try (FileReader file = new FileReader("test.txt")) {
    System.out.println("File opened");
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
}
// Advantage: Auto closes resources.
